{"title_page": "Adolfo Zald\u00edvar", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name      = Adolfo Zald\u00edvar\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image     = Adolfo_Zald\u00edvar.jpg\n|imagesize = \n|caption   = \n|nationality=[[Chile]]an\n|office      = Chilean Ambassador to Argentina\n|term_start  = April 16, 2010\n|term_end    = February 27, 2013\n|predecessor = Miguel Otero\n|successor   = Milenko Skoknic\n|office2      = [[Senate of Chile|Senator of Chile]]<br /> <small> [[Aisen Region|For Aisen Region]]\n|term_start2  = March 11, 1994\n|term_end2    = March 11, 2010\n|predecessor2 = Hern\u00e1n Vodanovic\n|successor2   = [[Patricio Walker]]\n|office3     = [[President of the Senate of Chile]]\n|term_start3 = March 12, 2008\n|term_end3   = March 13, 2009\n|predecessor3 = [[Eduardo Frei Ruiz-Tagle]]\n|successor3   = [[Jovino Novoa]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1943|9|13|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], [[Chile]]\n|dead=\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|2013|02|27|1943|9|13|mf=y}}\n|death_place=\n|resting_place = [[Parque del Recuerdo (Chile)|Parque del Recuerdo]]\n|occupation=[[Lawyer]]\n|spouse= Mar\u00eda Alicia Larra\u00edn\n|party=[[Partido Regionalista de los Independientes]] <small>(2009-2010)</small><br /> [[Christian Democrat Party of Chile]] <small>(1957\u20132007)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Miguel Adolfo Gerardo Zald\u00edvar Larra\u00edn''' (September 13, 1943 \u2013 February 27, 2013) was a [[Chile]]an politician and lawyer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/politica/2013/02/674-511050-9-a-los-69-anos-fallece-el-embajador-de-chile-en-argentina-y-ex-senador-adolfo.shtml |title=Adolfo Zald\u00edvar: A los 69 a\u00f1os fallece el embajador de Chile en Argentina y ex senador &#124; Pol\u00edtica |publisher=La Tercera |date=1990-01-01 |accessdate=2013-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227222506/http://www.latercera.com/noticia/politica/2013/02/674-511050-9-a-los-69-anos-fallece-el-embajador-de-chile-en-argentina-y-ex-senador-adolfo.shtml |archivedate=2013-02-27 }}</ref> He was senator for [[Ais\u00e9n Region|Ais\u00e9n]] and from March 2008 until his death in February 2013 he had been [[List of Presidents of the Senate of Chile|President of the Chilean Senate]]. He was an historic member of the [[Christian Democratic Party of Chile|Christian Democratic Party]] until his expulsion from the political party in December 2007.\n\nZald\u00edvar was married to Mar\u00eda Alicia Larra\u00edn Shaux and had six children. He was the brother of former President of the [[Senate of Chile]] and Interior Minister [[Andr\u00e9s Zald\u00edvar]].\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early life===\nZald\u00edvar received secondary formation at the ''Instituto de Humanidades Luis Campino''. Then, he went to university at the [[law faculty]] of the [[Catholic University of Chile|Catholic University]] in Chile, which he concluded in 1967. As a partner at the law firm \"Irureta, Zaldivar, Briones y Hern\u00e1ndez\", he worked in his profession until he finished his studies.\n\n===Political life===\nIn 1965 Zald\u00edvar became the university party leader of the Christian Democrat Party (PDC), and from 1970 to 1972 he occupied the post of national counselor for youth of this party. In the following year he became the national leader of the lawyers of the PDC, and filled this position until 1980. He was a co-founder of the Chilean Commission of [[Human Rights]].\n\nFrom 1985 to 1988 Zald\u00edvar was president of the Forum of Political Integration of [[Chile]] and [[Argentina]]. From 1983 to 1989 he was part of the fiscal commission of the PDC. Then from 1983 to 1990 he worked as national counselor of the PDC, then he became premier national vice-president.\n\nIn the [[election]]s of December 1993 Zald\u00edvar was elected senator, and formed the senate's mining commission. He went on to form the commission on national defense and the commission of maritime interests, fishing and [[aquaculture]]. From 2002 to 2006 he was president of the PDC.\n\n====Party expulsion====\nIn early 2006, after he lost the presidency of the PDC to [[Soledad Alvear]], Zald\u00edvar became a vocal critic of the Chilean economic system and voiced his disappointment with the government's \"unwillingness\" to amend it. He frequently came into conflict with Alvear and in August 2007 the Christian Democrat Party's Supreme Tribunal chastised him for his criticisms. Additionally, he was one of the harshest critics of the [[Transantiago]] public transport system, created under the leadership of the [[Concertaci\u00f3n]] coalition to which the Christian Democrats belonged. In November 2007, Zald\u00edvar, together with senators from the [[Alliance for Chile]] and independents [[Fernando Flores]] and [[Carlos Bianchi]], voted against continued funding for the Transantiago, against the wishes of his party's leadership. Alvear and her followers accused Zald\u00edvar of \"siding with the right\" and requested his expulsion from the party. In December, the party leadership formally presented the expulsion request to the Supreme Tribunal of the party, on the basis of his decision to ignore the party wishes on the Transantiago funding bill and for Zald\u00edvar's harsh criticisms of the leadership's actions regarding corruption. The Tribunal finally decided to expel Zald\u00edvar on December 27, 2007. On March 12, 2008 he became President of the Senate with the votes from the right-wing Alliance for Chile.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Commons category|Adolfo Zald\u00edvar}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080228045903/http://www.adolfozaldivar.cl/ Official site]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box\n| title=[[Senate of Chile|President of the Senate of Chile]]\n| before=[[Eduardo Frei Ruiz-Tagle]]\n| after=[[Jovino Novoa]]\n| years='''2008\u20132009'''}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{Succession box\n| title=[[Christian Democrat Party of Chile|Christian Democrat Party President]]\n| before=[[Ricardo Hormaz\u00e1bal]]\n| after=[[Soledad Alvear]]\n| years='''2002\u20132006'''}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of the Senate of Chile}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaldivar, Adolfo}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Senate of Chile]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Chile]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Chile to Argentina]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Catholic University of Chile alumni]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Party (Chile) politicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name      = Adolfo Zald\u00edvar\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image     = Adolfo_Zald\u00edvar.jpg\n|imagesize = \n|caption   = \n|nationality=[[Chile]]an\n|office      = Chilean Ambassador to Argentina\n|term_start  = April 16, 2010\n|term_end    = February 27, 2013\n|predecessor = Miguel Otero\n|successor   = Milenko Skoknic\n|office2      = [[Senate of Chile|Senator of Chile]]<br /> <small> [[Aisen Region|For Aisen Region]]\n|term_start2  = March 11, 1994\n|term_end2    = March 11, 2010\n|predecessor2 = Hern\u00e1n Vodanovic\n|successor2   = [[Patricio Walker]]\n|office3     = [[President of the Senate of Chile]]\n|term_start3 = March 12, 2008\n|term_end3   = March 13, 2009\n|predecessor3 = [[Eduardo Frei Ruiz-Tagle]]\n|successor3   = [[Jovino Novoa]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1943|9|13|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], [[Chile]]\n|dead=\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|2013|02|27|1943|9|13|mf=y}}\n|death_place=\n|resting_place = [[Parque del Recuerdo (Chile)|Parque del Recuerdo]]\n|occupation=[[Civil engineering|Lawyer]]\n|spouse= Mar\u00eda Alicia Larra\u00edn\n|party=[[Partido Regionalista de los Independientes]] <small>(2009-2010)</small><br /> [[Christian Democrat Party of Chile]] <small>(1957\u20132007)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Miguel Adolfo Gerardo Zald\u00edvar Larra\u00edn''' (September 13, 1943 \u2013 February 27, 2013) was a [[Chile]]an politician and lawyer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/politica/2013/02/674-511050-9-a-los-69-anos-fallece-el-embajador-de-chile-en-argentina-y-ex-senador-adolfo.shtml |title=Adolfo Zald\u00edvar: A los 69 a\u00f1os fallece el embajador de Chile en Argentina y ex senador &#124; Pol\u00edtica |publisher=La Tercera |date=1990-01-01 |accessdate=2013-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227222506/http://www.latercera.com/noticia/politica/2013/02/674-511050-9-a-los-69-anos-fallece-el-embajador-de-chile-en-argentina-y-ex-senador-adolfo.shtml |archivedate=2013-02-27 }}</ref> He was senator for [[Ais\u00e9n Region|Ais\u00e9n]] and from March 2008 until his death in February 2013 he had been [[List of Presidents of the Senate of Chile|President of the Chilean Senate]]. He was an historic member of the [[Christian Democratic Party of Chile|Christian Democratic Party]] until his expulsion from the political party in December 2007.\n\nZald\u00edvar was married to Mar\u00eda Alicia Larra\u00edn Shaux and had six children. He was the brother of former President of the [[Senate of Chile]] and Interior Minister [[Andr\u00e9s Zald\u00edvar]].\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early life===\nZald\u00edvar received secondary formation at the ''Instituto de Humanidades Luis Campino''. Then, he went to university at the [[law faculty]] of the [[Catholic University of Chile|Catholic University]] in Chile, which he concluded in 1967. As a partner at the law firm \"Irureta, Zaldivar, Briones y Hern\u00e1ndez\", he worked in his profession until he finished his studies.\n\n===Political life===\nIn 1965 Zald\u00edvar became the university party leader of the Christian Democrat Party (PDC), and from 1970 to 1972 he occupied the post of national counselor for youth of this party. In the following year he became the national leader of the lawyers of the PDC, and filled this position until 1980. He was a co-founder of the Chilean Commission of [[Human Rights]].\n\nFrom 1985 to 1988 Zald\u00edvar was president of the Forum of Political Integration of [[Chile]] and [[Argentina]]. From 1983 to 1989 he was part of the fiscal commission of the PDC. Then from 1983 to 1990 he worked as national counselor of the PDC, then he became premier national vice-president.\n\nIn the [[election]]s of December 1993 Zald\u00edvar was elected senator, and formed the senate's mining commission. He went on to form the commission on national defense and the commission of maritime interests, fishing and [[aquaculture]]. From 2002 to 2006 he was president of the PDC.\n\n====Party expulsion====\nIn early 2006, after he lost the presidency of the PDC to [[Soledad Alvear]], Zald\u00edvar became a vocal critic of the Chilean economic system and voiced his disappointment with the government's \"unwillingness\" to amend it. He frequently came into conflict with Alvear and in August 2007 the Christian Democrat Party's Supreme Tribunal chastised him for his criticisms. Additionally, he was one of the harshest critics of the [[Transantiago]] public transport system, created under the leadership of the [[Concertaci\u00f3n]] coalition to which the Christian Democrats belonged. In November 2007, Zald\u00edvar, together with senators from the [[Alliance for Chile]] and independents [[Fernando Flores]] and [[Carlos Bianchi]], voted against continued funding for the Transantiago, against the wishes of his party's leadership. Alvear and her followers accused Zald\u00edvar of \"siding with the right\" and requested his expulsion from the party. In December, the party leadership formally presented the expulsion request to the Supreme Tribunal of the party, on the basis of his decision to ignore the party wishes on the Transantiago funding bill and for Zald\u00edvar's harsh criticisms of the leadership's actions regarding corruption. The Tribunal finally decided to expel Zald\u00edvar on December 27, 2007. On March 12, 2008 he became President of the Senate with the votes from the right-wing Alliance for Chile.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Commons category|Adolfo Zald\u00edvar}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080228045903/http://www.adolfozaldivar.cl/ Official site]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box\n| title=[[Senate of Chile|President of the Senate of Chile]]\n| before=[[Eduardo Frei Ruiz-Tagle]]\n| after=[[Jovino Novoa]]\n| years='''2008\u20132009'''}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{Succession box\n| title=[[Christian Democrat Party of Chile|Christian Democrat Party President]]\n| before=[[Ricardo Hormaz\u00e1bal]]\n| after=[[Soledad Alvear]]\n| years='''2002\u20132006'''}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of the Senate of Chile}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaldivar, Adolfo}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Senate of Chile]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Chile]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Chile to Argentina]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Catholic University of Chile alumni]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Party (Chile) politicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n", "name_user": "Estin Gi\u00e7 Gi\u00e7", "label": "safe", "comment": "Lawyer or Civil engineer?", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adolfo_Zald%C3%ADvar"}
{"title_page": "Bihar Public Service Commission", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{short description|State government agency}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Bihar Public Service Commission\n|image        = Emblem of India.svg\n|image_border = \n|size         = 150px\n|alt          = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n|caption      = \n|map          = <!-- optional -->\n|msize        = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px -->\n|malt         = <!-- map alt text -->\n|mcaption     = <!-- optional -->\n|abbreviation = BPSC\n|motto        = \n|formation    = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1956|11|01}}\n|extinction   = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n|type         = GOVT.\n|status       = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n|purpose      = Recruitment\n|headquarters = [[Patna]], [[Bihar]]\n|location     = \n|coords       = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template -->\n|region_served =Bihar\n|members  = Prof. (Dr.) Ram Kishore Singh ,\n\nShri Shakti Samant,\nShri Pradeep Kumar Pandey\n|language     = <!-- official languages -->\n|leader_title =Chairman\n|leader_name  =  Shri Shishir Sinha\n|main_organ   = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n|parent_organization = <!-- if one -->\n|affiliations = <!-- if any -->\n|num_staff    = 1600\n|num_volunteers =\n|budget       = \n|website      = {{URL|http://bpsc.bih.nic.in/}}\n|remarks      =\n}}\nThe '''Bihar Public Service Commission''' ('''BPSC''') is a body created by the [[Constitution of India]] to select applicants for [[civil service]] jobs in the [[Indian state]] of [[Bihar]] according to the merits of the applicants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-02-09/patna/37007522_1_upsc-civil-servants-ips-officers |title=Choose 'servants', not 'rulers': CM's advice to UPSC |publisher=The Times of India |date=2013-02-09 |accessdate=2013-04-30}}</ref><ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/bpsc-prelims-hc-relief-to-aspirants-challenged/articleshow/57069169.cms BPSC prelims: HC relief to aspirants challenged]</ref><ref>[https://www.sarkariresults247.com/2020/04/bpsc-65th-mains-online-form-2020.html BPSC 65th Mains Online Form 2020]</ref>\n\n==History of Bihar Public Service Commission==\nThe history of [[Constitution of India]] reveals that the concept of conducting competitive examination for appointment to certain posts came into consideration way back in the year 1853 and a committee for giving shape to that was constituted under the chairmanship of [[Lord Macaulay]] in the year 1854. Later on the Federal Public Service Commission and the State Public Service Commissions were constituted under the [[Government of India Act 1935]]\nThe Bihar Public Service Commission came into existence from 1 April 1949 after its separation from the Commission for the States of [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]], in accordance with sub-section (1) of section 261 of the [[Government of India Act 1935]], as adapted. Its constitutional status was pronounced with the promulgation of [[Constitution of India]] on 26 January 1950. It is a [[Constitutional body]] under Article 315 of the [[Constitution of India]].\nThe Bihar Public Service Commission initially began its functioning for the State of [[Bihar]] with its headquarters at Ranchi. The State Government decided to shift the headquarters of the Commission from [[Ranchi]] to [[Patna]] and it was finally shifted to [[Patna]] on 1 March 1951.\nThe first Chairman of the Bihar Public Service Commission was Shri Rajandhari Sinha. Shri Radha Krishna Choudhary was the first Secretary to the Commission. The Bihar Public Service Commission (Conditions of Service) Regulations, 1960 was framed by the State of Bihar in exercise of the powers conferred by Article 318 of the Constitution of India and in supersession of the Regulation published with the Appointment Department's notification no. A-2654 dated 31 March 1953. Under Rule 3 of the Regulations, 1960 the Commission was constituted with a Chairman and 10 (ten) other members. The strength of members was reduced to 6 (six) after bifurcation of the State of [[Bihar]] and the State of [[Jharkhand]] vide notification no. 7/PSC-1013/95 (Part-3) Per 8262 dated 9 October 2002 of the Personnel & Administrative Reforms Department, [[Bihar]].\n\n==The Mandate of Bihar Public Service Commission.==\nArticle 320 and 321 of the [[Constitution of India]] prescribes the mandate of the State Public Service Commissions, which are:<br />\na)Recruitment by conduct of Competitive Examinations/ through interviews to the services of the State Government.<br />\nb)Advising the State Government on the suitability of officers on appointment on promotion as well as transfer from one service to the other.<br />\nc)Advising the State Government on the matters related with recruitment to various services and posts, framing and amendment of recruitment Rules.<br />\nd)Advising the State Government in all disciplinary cases relating to different civil services.<br />\ne)Advising the State Government in the matter of grant of extraordinary pension, reimbursement of legal expenses, etc.<br />\nf)Advising the State Government on any matter referred to the Commission by the Governor of Bihar,\n\n==Recruitment==\nRecruitment is made by two methods<br />\n'''Direct Recruitment:'''-Direct recruitment is made mainly by way of conducting competitive examination in which the selection is done on the basis of either of the following procedures.<br />\na)Main (Written) Examination and Interview of the successful candidates of the Preliminary Test prescribed under rules..<br />\nb)Written Examination (Mains).<br />\nc)Interview.<br />\n'''Promotion:'''-Promotion is granted to civil servants through the Departmental Promotion Committee (under the chairmanship of the Commission) constituted for the same and in accordance with the rules framed by the State Government.\n\n==Annual Report==\nArticle 323 of the Constitution of India prescribes for the submission of annual report of the work done by the State Public Service Commission to the Governor of the State. The Bihar Public Service Commission accordingly submits annual report of the work done by the Commission to the Governor of Bihar.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Union Public Service Commission]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://bpsc.bih.nic.in/}}\n\n{{State agencies of Bihar}}\n{{Public Service Commissions in India}}\n\n[[Category:State public service commissions of India]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1956]]\n[[Category:State agencies of Bihar]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{short description|State government agency}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Bihar Public Service Commission\n|image        = Emblem of India.svg\n|image_border = \n|size         = 150px\n|alt          = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n|caption      = \n|map          = <!-- optional -->\n|msize        = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px -->\n|malt         = <!-- map alt text -->\n|mcaption     = <!-- optional -->\n|abbreviation = BPSC\n|motto        = \n|formation    = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1956|11|01}}\n|extinction   = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n|type         = GOVT.\n|status       = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n|purpose      = Recruitment\n|headquarters = [[Patna]], [[Bihar]]\n|location     = \n|coords       = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template -->\n|region_served =Bihar\n|members  = Prof. (Dr.) Ram Kishore Singh ,\n\nShri Shakti Samant,\nShri Pradeep Kumar Pandey\n|language     = <!-- official languages -->\n|leader_title =Chairman\n|leader_name  =  Shri Shishir Sinha\n|main_organ   = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n|parent_organization = <!-- if one -->\n|affiliations = <!-- if any -->\n|num_staff    = 1600\n|num_volunteers =\n|budget       = \n|website      = {{URL|http://bpsc.bih.nic.in/}}\n|remarks      =\n}}\nThe '''Bihar Public Service Commission''' ('''BPSC''') is a body created by the [[Constitution of India]] to select applicants for [[civil service]] jobs in the [[Indian state]] of [[Bihar]] according to the merits of the applicants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-02-09/patna/37007522_1_upsc-civil-servants-ips-officers |title=Choose 'servants', not 'rulers': CM's advice to UPSC |publisher=The Times of India |date=2013-02-09 |accessdate=2013-04-30}}</ref><ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/bpsc-prelims-hc-relief-to-aspirants-challenged/articleshow/57069169.cms BPSC prelims: HC relief to aspirants challenged]</ref><ref>[https://www.sarkariresults247.com/2020/04/bpsc-65th-mains-online-form-2020.html BPSC 65th Mains Online Form 2020]</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sarkariresults247.com/2020/04/bpsc-65th-mains-online-form-2020.html |title=BPSC 65th Mains Online Form 2020 |publisher=Sarkari Results247 |date=2020-02-09 |accessdate=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>[https://www.sarkariresults247.com/2020/04/bpsc-65th-mains-online-form-2020.html BPSC 65th Mains Online Form 2020]</ref>\n\n\n==History of Bihar Public Service Commission==\nThe history of [[Constitution of India]] reveals that the concept of conducting competitive examination for appointment to certain posts came into consideration way back in the year 1853 and a committee for giving shape to that was constituted under the chairmanship of [[Lord Macaulay]] in the year 1854. Later on the Federal Public Service Commission and the State Public Service Commissions were constituted under the [[Government of India Act 1935]]\nThe Bihar Public Service Commission came into existence from 1 April 1949 after its separation from the Commission for the States of [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]], in accordance with sub-section (1) of section 261 of the [[Government of India Act 1935]], as adapted. Its constitutional status was pronounced with the promulgation of [[Constitution of India]] on 26 January 1950. It is a [[Constitutional body]] under Article 315 of the [[Constitution of India]].\nThe Bihar Public Service Commission initially began its functioning for the State of [[Bihar]] with its headquarters at Ranchi. The State Government decided to shift the headquarters of the Commission from [[Ranchi]] to [[Patna]] and it was finally shifted to [[Patna]] on 1 March 1951.\nThe first Chairman of the Bihar Public Service Commission was Shri Rajandhari Sinha. Shri Radha Krishna Choudhary was the first Secretary to the Commission. The Bihar Public Service Commission (Conditions of Service) Regulations, 1960 was framed by the State of Bihar in exercise of the powers conferred by Article 318 of the Constitution of India and in supersession of the Regulation published with the Appointment Department's notification no. A-2654 dated 31 March 1953. Under Rule 3 of the Regulations, 1960 the Commission was constituted with a Chairman and 10 (ten) other members. The strength of members was reduced to 6 (six) after bifurcation of the State of [[Bihar]] and the State of [[Jharkhand]] vide notification no. 7/PSC-1013/95 (Part-3) Per 8262 dated 9 October 2002 of the Personnel & Administrative Reforms Department, [[Bihar]].\n\n==The Mandate of Bihar Public Service Commission.==\nArticle 320 and 321 of the [[Constitution of India]] prescribes the mandate of the State Public Service Commissions, which are:<br />\na)Recruitment by conduct of Competitive Examinations/ through interviews to the services of the State Government.<br />\nb)Advising the State Government on the suitability of officers on appointment on promotion as well as transfer from one service to the other.<br />\nc)Advising the State Government on the matters related with recruitment to various services and posts, framing and amendment of recruitment Rules.<br />\nd)Advising the State Government in all disciplinary cases relating to different civil services.<br />\ne)Advising the State Government in the matter of grant of extraordinary pension, reimbursement of legal expenses, etc.<br />\nf)Advising the State Government on any matter referred to the Commission by the Governor of Bihar,\n\n==Recruitment==\nRecruitment is made by two methods<br />\n'''Direct Recruitment:'''-Direct recruitment is made mainly by way of conducting competitive examination in which the selection is done on the basis of either of the following procedures.<br />\na)Main (Written) Examination and Interview of the successful candidates of the Preliminary Test prescribed under rules..<br />\nb)Written Examination (Mains).<br />\nc)Interview.<br />\n'''Promotion:'''-Promotion is granted to civil servants through the Departmental Promotion Committee (under the chairmanship of the Commission) constituted for the same and in accordance with the rules framed by the State Government.\n\n==Annual Report==\nArticle 323 of the Constitution of India prescribes for the submission of annual report of the work done by the State Public Service Commission to the Governor of the State. The Bihar Public Service Commission accordingly submits annual report of the work done by the Commission to the Governor of Bihar.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Union Public Service Commission]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://bpsc.bih.nic.in/}}\n\n{{State agencies of Bihar}}\n{{Public Service Commissions in India}}\n\n[[Category:State public service commissions of India]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1956]]\n[[Category:State agencies of Bihar]]\n", "name_user": "SushantSKkumar", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bihar_Public_Service_Commission"}
{"title_page": "Dondre Wright", "text_new": "{{short description|Professional Canadian football defensive back}}\n{{Infobox CFL biography\n|name=Dondre Wright\n|image=\n|image_upright=\n|caption=\n|team=Toronto Argonauts\n|number=\n|position1=[[Defensive back]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1994|4|7}}\n|birth_place=[[Ajax, Ontario]]\n|Height_ft=5\n|Height_in=10\n|Weight_lbs=210\n|college=[[Henderson State Reddies football|Henderson State]]<br>[[New Mexico Military Institute Broncos|New Mexico Military]]\n|high_school=[[Pickering High School, Ajax|Pickering High]]\n|CFLDraftedYear=2017\n|CFLDraftedRound=3\n|CFLDraftedPick=20\n|CFLDraftedTeam=[[Montreal Alouettes]]\n|playing_years1={{CFL Year|2017|2018}}\n|playing_team1=[[Montreal Alouettes]]\n|playing_years2={{CFL Year|2019}}\n|playing_team2=[[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n|playing_years3={{CFL Year|2020}}\u2013present\n|playing_team3=[[Toronto Argonauts]]\n|status=Active\n|import=no\n|career_highlights=\n|CFLEastAllStar=\n|CFL=dondre-wright-2/163170/\n}}\n'''Dondre Wright''' (born April 7, 1994) is a professional [[Canadian football]] [[defensive back]] for the [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL). He played [[college football]] for the [[New Mexico Military Institute Broncos]] and the [[Henderson State Reddies football|Henderson State Reddies]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/sports/football/cfl/montreal-alouettes/alouettes-dondre-wright-arrives-at-camp-brimming-with-confidence/|title=Alouettes' Dondre Wright arrives at camp brimming with confidence|publisher=[[Montreal Gazette]]|date=May 24, 2017|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Montreal Alouettes===\nWright was drafted by the [[Montreal Alouettes]] in the third round, 20th overall, in the [[2017 CFL Draft]] and signed with the club on May 17, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.montrealalouettes.com/2017/05/19/alouettes-sign-eight-2017-cfl-draftees/|title=Alouettes sign all eight 2017 CFL draftees|publisher=[[Montreal Alouettes]]|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> He made his professional debut on June 22, 2017 against the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]] where he recorded two defensive tackles and two special teams tackles. He played in all 18 regular season games during the [[2017 Montreal Alouettes season|2017 season]] where he finished with 45 defensive tackles, 12 special teams tackles, and one forced fumble. In [[2018 Montreal Alouettes season|2018]], he spent two stints on the injured list and only played in nine regular season games where he had just two special teams tackles.<ref name=\"2018 moves\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/transactions/?season=2018 |title=CFL Transactions, 2018 |publisher=[[Canadian Football League]] |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref> He was a full participant in the team's 2019 training camp, but was part of the Alouettes' final cuts on June 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.montrealalouettes.com/2019/06/08/alouettes-transactions-8/|title=Alouettes' transactions|publisher=[[Montreal Alouettes]]|date=June 8, 2019|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Winnipeg Blue Bombers===\nOn July 8, 2019, Wright was signed to a practice roster agreement by the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bluebombers.com/2019/07/08/bombers-add-defensive-back-dondre-wright/|title=Bombers add defensive back Dondre Wright|publisher=[[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]|date=July 8, 2019|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> He played in three regular season games of the Blue Bombers in 2019. He was on the practice roster when the team won the [[107th Grey Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://d3ham790trbkqy.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/6/2019/06/GREY-CUP-rosters.pdf|title=Grey Cup Depth Chart|publisher=[[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Toronto Argonauts===\nAfter becoming a [[free agent]], he signed with the [[Toronto Argonauts]] on December 16, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.argonauts.ca/2019/12/16/argos-add-two-canadians-five-americans/|title=Argos add two Canadians and five Americans|publisher=[[Toronto Argonauts]]|date=December 16, 2019|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.argonauts.ca/players/dondre-wright-2/163170/ Toronto Argonauts bio] \n*{{Twitter|Dondre_Wright|Dondre Wright}}\n\n{{Toronto Argonauts roster navbox}}\n{{107th Grey Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Dondre}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Montreal Alouettes players]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Blue Bombers players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Argonauts players]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Military Institute Broncos football players]]\n[[Category:Henderson State Reddies football players]]\n[[Category:Canadian football defensive backs]]\n[[Category:Players of Canadian football from Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Ajax, Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professional Canadian football defensive back}}\n{{Infobox CFL biography\n|name=Dondre Wright\n|image=\n|image_upright=\n|caption=\n|team=Toronto Argonauts\n|number=\n|position1=[[Defensive back]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1994|4|7}}\n|birth_place=[[Ajax, Ontario]]\n|Height_ft=5\n|Height_in=10\n|Weight_lbs=210\n|college=[[Henderson State Reddies football|Henderson State]]<br>[[New Mexico Military Institute Broncos|New Mexico Military]]\n|high_school=[[Pickering High School, Ajax|Pickering High]]\n|CFLDraftedYear=2017\n|CFLDraftedRound=3\n|CFLDraftedPick=20\n|CFLDraftedTeam=[[Montreal Alouettes]]\n|playing_years1={{CFL Year|2017|2018}}\n|playing_team1=[[Montreal Alouettes]]\n|playing_years2={{CFL Year|2019}}\n|playing_team2=[[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n|playing_years3={{CFL Year|2020}}\u2013present\n|playing_team3=[[Toronto Argonauts]]\n|status=Active\n|import=no\n|career_highlights=\n|CFLEastAllStar=\n|CFL=dondre-wright-2/163170/\n}}\n'''Dondre Wright''' (born April 7, 1994) is a professional [[Canadian football]] [[defensive back]] for the [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL). He played [[college football]] for the [[New Mexico Military Institute Broncos]] and the [[Henderson State Reddies football|Henderson State Reddies]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/sports/football/cfl/montreal-alouettes/alouettes-dondre-wright-arrives-at-camp-brimming-with-confidence/|title=Alouettes' Dondre Wright arrives at camp brimming with confidence|publisher=[[Montreal Gazette]]|date=May 24, 2017|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Montreal Alouettes===\nWright was drafted by the [[Montreal Alouettes]] in the third round, 20th overall, in the [[2017 CFL Draft]] and signed with the club on May 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.montrealalouettes.com/2017/05/19/alouettes-sign-eight-2017-cfl-draftees/|title=Alouettes sign all eight 2017 CFL draftees|publisher=[[Montreal Alouettes]]|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> He made his professional debut on June 22, 2017 against the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]] where he recorded two defensive tackles and two special teams tackles. He played in all 18 regular season games during the [[2017 Montreal Alouettes season|2017 season]] where he finished with 45 defensive tackles, 12 special teams tackles, and one forced fumble. In [[2018 Montreal Alouettes season|2018]], he spent two stints on the injured list and only played in nine regular season games where he had just two special teams tackles.<ref name=\"2018 moves\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/transactions/?season=2018 |title=CFL Transactions, 2018 |publisher=[[Canadian Football League]] |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref> He was a full participant in the team's 2019 training camp, but was part of the Alouettes' final cuts on June 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.montrealalouettes.com/2019/06/08/alouettes-transactions-8/|title=Alouettes' transactions|publisher=[[Montreal Alouettes]]|date=June 8, 2019|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Winnipeg Blue Bombers===\nOn July 8, 2019, Wright was signed to a practice roster agreement by the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bluebombers.com/2019/07/08/bombers-add-defensive-back-dondre-wright/|title=Bombers add defensive back Dondre Wright|publisher=[[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]|date=July 8, 2019|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> He played in three regular season games of the Blue Bombers in 2019. He was on the practice roster when the team won the [[107th Grey Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://d3ham790trbkqy.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/6/2019/06/GREY-CUP-rosters.pdf|title=Grey Cup Depth Chart|publisher=[[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Toronto Argonauts===\nAfter becoming a [[free agent]], he signed with the [[Toronto Argonauts]] on December 16, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.argonauts.ca/2019/12/16/argos-add-two-canadians-five-americans/|title=Argos add two Canadians and five Americans|publisher=[[Toronto Argonauts]]|date=December 16, 2019|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.argonauts.ca/players/dondre-wright-2/163170/ Toronto Argonauts bio] \n*{{Twitter|Dondre_Wright|Dondre Wright}}\n\n{{Toronto Argonauts roster navbox}}\n{{107th Grey Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Dondre}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Montreal Alouettes players]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Blue Bombers players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Argonauts players]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Military Institute Broncos football players]]\n[[Category:Henderson State Reddies football players]]\n[[Category:Canadian football defensive backs]]\n[[Category:Players of Canadian football from Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Ajax, Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Cmm3", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMontreal Alouettes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dondre_Wright"}
