{"title_page": "Pharae", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n'''Pharae''' ({{lang-grc|\u03a6\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03af}}),<ref>{{Cite Stephanus|''s.v.'' \u1f21 \u03a6\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae}}</ref> otherwise known as '''Phara''' (\u03a6\u1fb6\u03c1\u03b1),<ref>{{cite Strabo|viii. p.388}}</ref> and '''Pherae''',<ref>{{cite Pliny|4.6}}</ref> was a town and [[polis]] (city-state),<ref name=Poleis>{{cite book|author= Mogens Herman Hansen & Thomas Heine Nielsen |title= An inventory of archaic and classical poleis|year= 2004|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]|location=New York|isbn= 0-19-814099-1|chapter= Achaia|page= 485}}</ref> situated by the [[Peiros]] River, approximately {{convert|11|km}} from the sea and {{convert|23.5|km}} from the town of [[Patras]], in what is now southern [[Greece]]. It was one of the twelve Achaean cities, and one of the four major cities which spearheaded the restoration of the [[Achaean League]] in 280 BC. \n\nIn an event called the [[Social War (220\u2013217 BC)]], it suffered from various setbacks caused by the attacks of the [[Aetolian League|Aetolians]] and [[Elis|Eleans]]. Its territory was later annexed by [[Augustus]], and after the [[Battle of Actium]], it was made a colony of [[Roman Republic|Rome]]. \n\nAs of the 19th century, Pharae still contained a large agora with a statue of Hermes.<ref>{{cite DGRG|title=Pharae}}</ref> The modern village [[Fares (village)|Fares]] was named after Pharae.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DGRG|title=Pharae}}\n\n{{coord|38.082|N|21.73|E|source:http://dare.ht.lu.se/places/31042.html|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in ancient Achaea]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Greece]]\n[[Category:Cities in ancient Greece]]\n[[Category:Achaean city-states]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n'''Pharae''' ({{lang-grc|\u03a6\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03af}}),<ref>{{Cite Stephanus|''s.v.'' \u1f21 \u03a6\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae}}</ref> otherwise known as '''Phara''' (\u03a6\u1fb6\u03c1\u03b1),<ref>{{cite Strabo|viii. p.388}}</ref> and '''Pherae''',<ref>{{cite Pliny|4.6}}</ref> was a town and [[polis]] (city-state),<ref name=Poleis>{{cite book|author= Mogens Herman Hansen & Thomas Heine Nielsen |title= An inventory of archaic and classical poleis|year= 2004|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]|location=New York|isbn= 0-19-814099-1|chapter= Achaia|page= 485}}</ref> situated by the [[Peiros]] River, approximately {{convert|11|km}} from the sea and {{convert|23.5|km}} from the town of [[Patras]], in what is now southern [[Greece]]. It was one of the twelve Achaean cities, and one of the four major cities which spearheaded the restoration of the [[Achaean League]] in 280 BC. \n\nIn an event called the [[Social War (220\u2013217 BC)]], it suffered from various setbacks caused by the attacks of the [[Aetolian League|Aetolians]] and [[Elis|Eleans]]. Its territory was annexed by [[Augustus]], and after the [[Battle of Actium]], it was made a colony of [[Roman Republic|Rome]]. \n\nAs of the 19th century, Pharae still contained a large agora with a statue of Hermes.<ref>{{cite DGRG|title=Pharae}}</ref> The modern village [[Fares (village)|Fares]] was named after Pharae.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DGRG|title=Pharae}}\n\n{{coord|38.082|N|21.73|E|source:http://dare.ht.lu.se/places/31042.html|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in ancient Achaea]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Greece]]\n[[Category:Cities in ancient Greece]]\n[[Category:Achaean city-states]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharae"}
{"title_page": "Herman Chinery-Hesse", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian software entrepreneur}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Herman Chinery-Hesse\n| image              = Herman Chinery-Hesse.jpg\n| image_size         = 300\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1963}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| citizenship        = Ghana\n| traded_as          = \n| occupation         = founder of SOFTtribe\n| parents            = {{unbulleted list|[[Lebrecht James Chinery-Hesse]] (father)|[[Mary Chinery-Hesse]] (mother)}}\n| relatives          = {{unbulleted list|[[Hesse family]]|[[Robert Samuel Blay]] (grandfather)}}\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = 2\n| alma_mater         = {{unbulleted list|[[Mfantsipim School]]|[[Texas State University]]}}\n| net_worth          = |\n}}\n\n'''Herman Chinery-Hesse''' (born 1963) is a Ghanaian technology entrepreneur and the founder of SOFTtribe, the largest software company in [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1631_judges/page5.shtml|title=BBC Newsmaker|publisher=BBC|access-date=25 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502081312/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1631_judges/page5.shtml|archive-date=2 May 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbesafrica.com/entrepreneurs/2012/02/01/life-fast-lane-bill-gates-ghana/|title=Life In The Fast Lane With The Bill Gates Of Ghana|last=Africa|first=Forbes|date=2012-02-01|website=Forbes Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> He is popularly known as the [[Bill Gates]] of [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2012/aug/26/new-africa-ghana-software-chinery-hesse|title=New Africa: how an entrepreneur became 'the Bill Gates of Ghana'|publisher=theguardian|access-date=25 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521070239/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2012/aug/26/new-africa-ghana-software-chinery-hesse|archive-date=21 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2012-08-25|last1=Smith|first1=David}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14793780 |title=BBC News - African Dream: Ghana's Herman Chinery-Hesse |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-09-06 |access-date=2015-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216032752/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14793780 |archive-date=2014-12-16 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehabarinetwork.com/profile-herman-chinery-hesse-africas-father-of-technology |title=Profile: Herman Chinery-Hesse - \"Africa's father of Technology\" |publisher=The Habari Network |date=2012-01-27 |access-date=2015-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223012109/http://www.thehabarinetwork.com/profile-herman-chinery-hesse-africas-father-of-technology |archive-date=2015-02-23 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18784019 |title=BBC News - The mobile technologies making Africa cheaper and safer |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2012-07-13 |access-date=2015-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925142401/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18784019 |archive-date=2015-09-25 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/01/26/tech/herman-chinery-hesse-technology/ |title=Africa's 'father of technology' on sparking a tech revolution - CNN.com |publisher=Edition.cnn.com |date=2012-01-27 |access-date=2015-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223012558/http://edition.cnn.com/2012/01/26/tech/herman-chinery-hesse-technology/ |archive-date=2015-02-23 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Barber |first=Lionel |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/29e87512-8431-11e1-9d54-00144feab49a.html |title=Twelve days in west Africa: Accra, Ghana |publisher=FT.com |date=2012-04-17 |access-date=2015-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223023220/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/29e87512-8431-11e1-9d54-00144feab49a.html |archive-date=2015-02-23 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.inc.com/magazine/20081001/meet-the-bill-gates-of-ghana.html |title=Meet the Bill Gates of Ghana -Herman Chinery-Hesse - e-commerce in Africa |publisher=Inc.com |date=2008-10-01 |access-date=2015-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312024811/http://www.inc.com/magazine/20081001/meet-the-bill-gates-of-ghana.html |archive-date=2015-03-12 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Chinery-Hesse also made the list of 15 Black STEM Innovators.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana's Chinery-Hesse makes list of 15 Black STEM Innovators|url=http://citifmonline.com/2016/02/14/189647/|website=Citifmonline.com|publisher=Citi FM|access-date=17 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218141322/http://citifmonline.com/2016/02/14/189647/|archive-date=18 February 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2016-02-13}}</ref> In March 2019, he was introduced as the Commonwealth Chair for Business and Technology initiatives in Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2019/March-22nd/chinery-hesse-outdoored-as-cwealth-business-and-tech-african-chair.php|title=Chinery-Hesse outdoored as C'wealth Business and Tech African Chair|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2019-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323093911/https://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2019/March-22nd/chinery-hesse-outdoored-as-cwealth-business-and-tech-african-chair.php|archive-date=2019-03-23|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n{{further|Hesse family}}\nHerman Chinery-Hesse was born in [[Dublin]] in 1963 to [[Lebrecht James Chinery-Hesse|Lebrecht James Nii Tettey Chinery-Hesse]] and [[Mary Chinery-Hesse]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyguidenetwork.com/a-very-nice-man-goes-home/|title=A \"Very Nice Man\" Goes Home|date=2018-10-13|website=DailyGuide Network|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>  He was educated at the [[Mfantsipim School]] in [[Cape Coast]] and the [[Texas State University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2011-09-15-herman-chinery-hesse-africas-father-of-technology#.VOpkcHysV8E |title=Herman Chinery-Hesse, Africa's 'father of technology' |publisher=Daily Maverick |date=2011-09-15 |access-date=2015-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223065059/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2011-09-15-herman-chinery-hesse-africas-father-of-technology/#.VOpkcHysV8E |archive-date=2015-02-23 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He was the recipient of ''Distinguished Alumnus Award'' from the Texas State Alumni Association and Texas State University-San Marcos and the ''Outstanding Ghanaian Professional''.<ref>{{Citation|last=TEDx Talks|title=Powering the African marketplace: Herman Chinery-Hesse at TEDxEuston|date=2012-02-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=om1KZOCP3CU|access-date=2019-07-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101070047/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=om1KZOCP3CU|archive-date=2015-01-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chinery-Hesse, Herman}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Ga-Adangbe people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Hesse family of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mfantsipim School alumni]]\n[[Category:Texas State University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian software entrepreneur}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Herman Chinery-Hesse\n| image              = Herman Chinery-Hesse.jpg\n| image_size         = 300\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1963}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| citizenship        = Ghana\n| traded_as          = \n| occupatio