cf\n|{{BJS stations|Xinjiekou}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u65b0\u8857\u53e3}}}}\n|\n|{{small|7 47 105 111 508 \u591c36}}\n|1.025\n|15.123\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Ping'anli}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u5e73\u5b89\u91cc}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|6}}\n|{{small|3 13 22 38 42 88 105 107 111 118 332 409 701 \u727913 \u591c3 \u591c4 \u591c10 \u591c21}}\n|1.100\n|16.223\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Xisi}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u897f\u56db}}}}\n|\n|{{small|3 13 22 38 42 88 101 102 103 105 109 124 332 409 612 \u727913 \u591c4 \u591c10 \u591c13}}\n|1.100\n|17.323\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Lingjing Hutong}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u7075\u5883\u80e1\u540c}}}}\n|\n|{{small|22 38 46 68 88 102 105 109 \u727913 \u591c4 \u591c10}}\n|0.869\n|18.192\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Xidan}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u897f\u5355}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|1}}\n|{{small|1 15 22 52 70 83 88 102 105 109 332 \u727913 \u591c1 \u591c4 \u591c10}}\n|1.011\n|19.203\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Xuanwumen}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u5ba3\u6b66\u95e8}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|2}}\n|{{small|7 9 15 22 44 67 70 83 102 105 109 332 \u72792 \u72794 \u72797 \u727913 \u727914 \u591c4 \u591c5 \u591c10}}\n|0.815\n|20.018\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Caishikou}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u83dc\u5e02\u53e3}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|7}}\n|{{small|5 6 48 57 70 83 102 105 109 381 \u727914 \u591c4 \u591c7 \u591c10 \u591c18 \u4e1313}}\n|1.152\n|21.170\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf \n|{{BJS stations|Taoranting}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u9676\u7136\u4ead}}}}\n|\n|{{small|40 59 83 133 381 \u727914 \u591c4 \u591c18 \u591c23 \u4e1313}}\n|1.200\n|22.370\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|[[Beijing South railway station]]\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u5317\u4eac\u5357\u7ad9}}}}\n| {{rint|beijing|14}} {{nowrap|{{rint|cn|rail}} {{rint|cn|crh|link=Beijing South railway station}} [[Beijing South railway station|VNP]]}} {{RouteBox|Jingjin|Beijing\u2013Tianjin intercity railway|#{{CR color|intercity}}}}\n|{{small|20 25 102 106 133 343 381 458 485 529 652 665 \u727917 \u591c15 \u591c17 \u591c24 \u4e1353}}\n|1.643\n|24.013\n|style = \"border-bottom:solid 0;\" rowspan=\"4\"|[[Fengtai District|Fengtai]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf \n|{{BJS stations|Majiapu}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u9a6c\u5bb6\u5821}}}}\n|\n|{{small|51 66 72 485 501 529 603 998 \u727914 \u591c18 \u4e13145}}\n|1.480\n|25.493\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Jiaomen West}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u89d2\u95e8\u897f}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|10}}\n|{{small|51 72 474 501 529 556 646 998 \u727914 \u591c18 \u4e1326 \u4e13145}}\n|0.827\n|26.320\n|-\n|align=\"center\" style = \"border-bottom:solid 0;\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\" style = \"border-bottom:solid 0;\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Gongyixiqiao}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u516c\u76ca\u897f\u6865}}}}\n|\n|{{small|377 474 511 556 646 825 990 \u4e1326 \u4e13132 \u4e13145 \u4e13149}}\n|0.989\n|27.309\n|-\n| style = \"border-top:solid 0;\" |\n| style = \"border-top:solid 0;\" |\n| style = \"background:#{{BJS color|4}}; height: 2pt\" colspan = \"6\" |\n| style = \"border-top:solid 0; border-bottom:solid 0;\" |\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\u25cf||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Xingong}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u65b0\u5bab}}}}\n|\n|{{small|343 353 369 474 556 685 827 829 946 954 \u4e1359 \u4e1367 \u4e13149}}\n|colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"11\"|{{small|''see<br>[[Daxing line]]''}}\n|style = \"border-top:solid 0;\" rowspan=\"1\"|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Xihongmen}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u897f\u7ea2\u95e8}}}}\n|\n|{{small|381 454 470 474 483 646 829 993 \u4e1384 \u4e1397 \u4e13169}}\n|rowspan=\"10\"|[[Daxing District|Daxing]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf \n|{{BJS stations|Gaomidian North}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u9ad8\u7c73\u5e97\u5317}}}}\n|\n|{{small|631}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Gaomidian South}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u9ad8\u7c73\u5e97\u5357}}}}\n|\n|{{small|937 \u4e1324}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf \n|{{BJS stations|Zaoyuan}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u67a3\u56ed}}}}\n|\n|{{small|410 631\u5feb 829 841 842 844 937 940 954 968}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf \n|{{BJS stations|Qingyuanlu}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u6e05\u6e90\u8def}}}}\n|\n|{{small|456 631 631\u5feb 829 841 934 940 947 954 968 969 \u4e1323}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Huangcun Xidajie}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u9ec4\u6751\u897f\u5927\u8857}}}}\n|\n|{{small|456 631 631\u5feb 829 840 934 940 947 954 968}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|[[Huangcun railway station]]\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u9ec4\u6751\u706b\u8f66\u7ad9}}}}\n| {{nowrap|{{rint|cn|rail|link=Huangcun railway station}} [[Huangcun railway station|HCP]]}}\n|{{small|366 366\u5feb 369 631 631\u5feb 827 829 840 947 957 968 969}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Yihezhuang}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u4e49\u548c\u5e84}}}}\n|\n|{{small|456 934}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Biomedical Base}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u751f\u7269\u533b\u836f\u57fa\u5730}}}}\n|\n|{{small|456 827 842}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Tiangongyuan}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u5929\u5bab\u9662}}}}\n|\n|{{small|456 827 829 842}}\n|- style = \"background:#{{BJS color|Daxing}}; height: 2pt\"\n| colspan = \"9\" |\n|}\n\n==Planning and construction==\nPlans for Line 4 date back to the 1950s when Beijing's [[Line 1, Beijing Subway|first subway line]] was still under construction. It was planned to run from the [[Summer Palace]], east towards [[Xizhimen]], southeast to [[Zhongshan Park (Beijing)|Zhongshan Park]], terminating at the Beijing Stadium, which near today's [[Tiantandongmen Station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/theory/2007-09/28/content_6799411.htm|script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u8bde\u751f\u8bb0:\u5468\u603b\u7406\u79f0\u7b79\u5efa\u5730\u94c1\u662f\u4e3a\u5907\u6218|accessdate=2009-05-03|date=2007-09-28|language=zh}}</ref> Ultimately, the section between Summer Palace to Xizhimen was built as planned. However, construction only formally started in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sohu.com/20040810/n221446103.shtml|script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c14\u53f7\u7ebf5\u8f66\u7ad9\u5f00\u5de5 \u6b8b\u75be\u4eba\u6709\u4e13\u7528\u7535\u68af|date=2004-08-10|accessdate=2009-05-03|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nOn December 3, 2004 Hong Kong's [[MTR Corporation]], Beijing Infrastructure Investment Co., Ltd., and Beijing Capital Group Co., Ltd. signed the Beijing Metro Line 4, investment, construction, operation principle of cooperation agreement, making Line 4 the Mainland China's first rail transit line financed using a public-private partnership framework. Subsequently, on November 8, 2005, a joint venture among the 3 companies was established. The Hong Kong MTRC will invest 735 million RMB to the construction of Line 4 and in return have the right to operate Line 4 for 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://finance.sina.com.cn/g/20050208/08281356844.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e03\u4ebf\u6e2f\u8d44\u6ce8\u5165\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c14\u53f7\u7ebf \u9996\u521b\u516c\u79c1\u5408\u8425\u6a21\u5f0f|accessdate=2009-05-03|date=2005-02-08|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2009, the construction of Line 4 is nearing completion with all tunnels bored.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/c/2009-02-10/125817184920.shtml|script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c14\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5168\u7ebf\u8d2f\u901a 9\u6708\u5f00\u59cb\u8fd0\u8425|date=2009-02-10|accessdate=2009-05-03|language=zh}}</ref> In March 6, four subway trains begin testing while Hong Kong's then Chief Executive, [[Donald Tsang]], visited the project.<ref name=elec>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtr.bj.cn/news/detail66.htm|script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c14\u53f7\u7ebf\u5168\u7ebf\u5b9e\u73b0\u7535\u901a \u88c5\u4fee\u8fdb\u5c55\u987a\u5229 \u4e3b\u6253\u5730\u57df\u7279\u8272|accessdate=2009-11-27|language=zh}}</ref> On September 28, 2009, Line 4 was officially opened for trial operation. Bringing the number of subway lines in Beijing to 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinmin.cn/rollnews/2009/09/28/2649497.html|script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c14\u53f7\u7ebf\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425 \u4e0b\u53483\u65f6\u8d77\u8f7d\u5ba2\u8fd0\u8425|date=2009-09-28|accessdate=2009-09-28|language=zh}}</ref> On December 30, 2010, the Daxing line started trial operation, with direct service into Line 4. Creating a {{convert|50|km|abbr=on}} long line with 35 stations.<ref name=\"dxopen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtr.bj.cn/news/detail315.htm |script-title=zh:\u5927\u5174\u7ebf12\u670830\u65e5\u4e24\u70b9\u5f00\u95e8\u8fce\u5ba2 |publisher=[[Beijing MTR]] |date=2010-12-30 |accessdate=2011-01-14 |language=zh |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110109034023/http://www.mtr.bj.cn/news/detail315.htm |archivedate=2011-01-09 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, planners in Haidian District have proposed extending the line to the north by {{convert|8|km|abbr=on}} with four additional stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.cctv.com/china/20090107/100614.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u660e\u5e74\u6709\u671b\u901a\u9999\u5c71 \u897f\u957f\u5b89\u8857\u6cbf\u7ebf\u9053\u8def\u6269\u5bbd_CCTV.com_\u4e2d\u56fd\u4e2d\u592e\u7535\u89c6\u53f0 |publisher=[[CCTV News]] |access-date=2018-06-16}}</ref> The planned stations have been identified as '''Baiwangshan''' ({{lang|zh|\u767e\u65fa\u5c71}}), '''Xibeiwang''' ({{lang|zh|\u897f\u5317\u65fa}}), '''[[Beijing Aerospace Command and Control Center|Aerospace City]] West''' ({{lang|zh|\u822a\u5929\u57ce\u897f}}), and '''Yongfeng''' ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6c38\u4e30}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinanews.com/sh/news/2008/01-09/1128656.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c14\u53f7\u7ebf\u62df\u5411\u5317\u5ef6\u957f8\u516c\u91cc \u589e\u8bbe\u56db\u5ea7\u8f66\u7ad9|last=chinanews|website=www.chinanews.com|access-date=2018-06-16}}</ref> However, by June 2010, Line 4's northern extension was cancelled and replaced by the northern extension of [[Line 16, Beijing Subway|Line 16]] which opened in 2016.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web |language=zh-hans |url=http://news.dichan.sina.com.cn/bj/2010/06/29/178474.html?source=rss |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c116\u53f7\u7ebf\u57ce\u897f\u8d2f\u901a\u5357\u5317 |publisher=[[:zh:\u6cd5\u5236\u665a\u62a5|\u6cd5\u5236\u665a\u62a5]] |date=2010-06-29 |title=Archived copy |access-date=8 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707022128/http://news.dichan.sina.com.cn/bj/2010/06/29/178474.html?source=rss |archive-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead }} 2010-06-29</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; text-align: right;\"\n!Segment!!Commencement!!Length!!Station(s)!!Name\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Anheqiao North \u2014 Gongyixiqiao\n| 28 September 2009\n| {{convert|28.2|km|mi|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=line4mtr />\n| 24\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| (initial phase)\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Gongyixiqiao \u2014 Tiangongyuan\n| 30 December 2010\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: left;\"| ''see [[Daxing line]]''\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| (through services)\n|}\n\n==Operation==\nUnlike the other lines of the Beijing Subway, which are completely state-owned and operated, Line 4 was built and is managed by the Beijing MTR Corp. Ltd., a three-way joint-venture among the Hong Kong [[MTR Corporation]], the Beijing Capital Group (\"BCG\"), and the Beijing Infrastructure Investment Co. (\"BIIC\").<ref name=autogenerated1 >[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200604/15/eng20060415_258614.html \"Hong Kong MTR Corp wins 30-year operation of new Beijing metro line\" ''People's Daily''] Apr. 15, 2006</ref> The Hong Kong MTR, which operates the [[MTR|Hong Kong Mass Transit Railway]], and the state-owned BCG each holds a 49% stake in the venture and the BIIC has 2%.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  The JV is responsible for 30% of the investment capital to build Line 4, mainly to finance the purchase of electrical and mechanical equipment, while the Beijing Municipal Government provided the remaining 70%, to cover civil engineering, station, and track work costs.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">[http://www.mtr.com.hk/eng/projects/china_beijing.html \"Beijing Metro Line 4\" Hong Kong MTR Corporate Site] Accessed on Jan. 6, 2009</ref>\n\nThe Beijing government has also awarded the JV a concession to manage Line 4 for 30 years.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  The PPP JV model was designed to introduce private capital as well as advanced metro management methods to the growing Beijing Subway.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Among the most visible differences in management of Line 4 is a ban on food and beverage consumption inside Line 4 trains and stations.<ref>{{cite web |language=zh-hans |url=http://www.china.com.cn/health/txt/2009-06/01/content_17867889.htm |author1=Chen Si |author2=Yan Xinhong |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c14\u53f7\u7ebf\u7981\u5403\u96f6\u98df\u559d\u996e\u6599 \u7ad9\u5385\u80fd\u9694\u6bd2\u6c14 |publisher=[[:zh:\u6cd5\u5236\u665a\u62a5|\u6cd5\u5236\u665a\u62a5]] |date=June 1, 2009}}</ref>\n==Rolling Stock==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; text-align: center;\"\n!Model!!Image!!Manufacturer!!Year Built!!Year Refurbished!!Amount in Service!!Fleet Numbers!!Depot\n|-\n| [[:zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1SFM05\u578b\u7535\u52a8\u8f66\u7ec4|SFM05]]\n| [[File:L4_010_exiting_Xihongmen_Station_(20170807182102).jpg|150px]]\n| [[CRRC Qingdao Sifang]]\n| 2009-2010\n| Never\n| 73\n| 001-040<br/>061-093\n| [[:zh:\u9f99\u80cc\u6751\u505c\u8f66\u573a|Longbeicun]]<br/>[[:zh:\u9a6c\u5bb6\u5821\u8f66\u8f86\u6bb5|Majiapu]]<br/>[[:zh:\u5357\u5146\u8def\u8f66\u8f86\u6bb5|Nanzhaolu]]\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery caption=\"\" widths=\"140px\" heights=\"\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Yuanmingyuan Station.jpg|[[Yuanmingyuan Park Station]]\nFile:Entrance D, East Gate of Peking University Station.JPG|[[East Gate of Peking University Station]] Exit D\nFile:Paint on the wall of East Gate of Peking University station.JPG|Mural at East Gate of Peking University Station\nFile:\u4e2d\u5173\u6751\u7ad9B\u51fa\u7ad9\u53e3.jpg|[[Zhongguancun Station]] Exit B\nFile:\u6d77\u6dc0\u9ec4\u5e84\u7ad9A2\u51fa\u53e3.JPG|[[Haidianhuangzhuang Station]] Exit A2\nFile:\u56fd\u5bb6\u56fe\u4e66\u9986\u7ad9\u6d6e\u96d5.jpg|Mural at National Library Station\nFile:20110819971 BeijingZooStation.jpg|[[Beijing Zoo Station]]\nFile:Xisi Station Beijing.jpg|[[Xisi Station]]\nFile:Exit D of Taoranting Station.jpg|[[Taoranting Station]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Line 4, Beijing Subway}}\n* [http://www.mtr.bj.cn/ Beijing MTR Corp. Ltd] official site\n\n{{Beijing transit}}\n{{Beijing Subway}}\n{{Beijing Subway Station\n|line4=yes\n}}\n\n[[Category:Beijing Subway lines]]\n[[Category:MTR Corporation]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2009]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n", "name_user": "Terramorphous", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_4_(Beijing_Subway)"}
{"title_page": "Jane Lynch", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress and comedian}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Jane Lynch\n| image = Jane Lynch at the 2016 Willfilm Awards.jpg\n| caption = Lynch at the 2016 Willfilm Awards\n| birth_name =  Jane Marie Lynch\n| birth_date =  {{birth date and age|1960|7|14}}\n| birth_place =  [[Evergreen Park, Illinois]], U.S.\n| education   = [[Illinois State University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Cornell University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*voice actress\n*singer\n*author\n*comedian\n}}\n| years_active = 1986\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lara Embry|2010|2014|reason=divorced}} \n| website = {{url|JaneLynchOfficial.com}}\n}}\n'''Jane Marie Lynch''' (born July 14, 1960)<ref name=filmref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/2/Jane-Lynch.html| title=Jane Lynch Biography (1960\u2013)| publisher=FilmReference.com|accessdate=January 19, 2017| archivedate= March 4, 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074538/http://www.filmreference.com/film/2/Jane-Lynch.html| url-status=live}} Note: Site gives Dalton, Illinois, as birth place, while Lynch in a ''Late Late Show'' source cited here gives Evergreen Park, Illinois.</ref> is an American actress, voice actress, singer, author, and comedian. She is best known for her role as [[Sue Sylvester]] in the musical television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''. She also gained fame in [[Christopher Guest]]'s \n[[improvisational theatre|improv]] [[mockumentary]] pictures such as ''[[Best in Show (film)|Best in Show]]''.<ref name=\"wired\" >{{cite web|title=Jane Lynch: 'I came wired with extra angst'|url= https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/sep/19/jane-lynch-emmy-awards-glee|work=The Guardian |date=September 19, 2011|accessdate=October 22, 2011|author=Freeman, Hadley}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/monkeysee/2011/09/16/140502205/jane-lynch-a-life-of-happy-accidents | title=Jane Lynch: A Life Of 'Happy Accidents' | publisher=[[NPR]] | date=September 16, 2011 | accessdate=November 21, 2011 | author=Holmes, Linda}}</ref><ref name=\"fivethings\">{{cite web|title=Jane Lynch: Five things you may not know about the Emmy host and 'Glee star'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/celebritology/post/jane-lynch-five-things-you-may-not-know-about-the-emmy-host-and-glee-star/2011/09/18/gIQA2ytccK_blog.html|work=The Washington Post|date=September 18, 2011|accessdate=October 22, 2011|last1=Chaney |first1=Jen}}</ref>\n\nA native of [[Dolton, Illinois]], Lynch's television cameos include an appearance in the [[Nickelodeon]] situation comedy ''[[iCarly]]'' and the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] dark comedy series ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]''. Lynch had a recurring role in the [[Warner Bros.]] situation comedy ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'' from 2004 to 2014 and was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for her performance in 2010. She has also had other notable roles in numerous [[mainstream]] comedies, such as ''[[Talladega Nights: The Ballad of Ricky Bobby]]'', ''[[The 40-Year-Old Virgin]]'', ''[[Role Models]]'' and ''[[The Three Stooges (2012 film)|The Three Stooges]]''.\n\nOn September 4, 2013, Lynch received the 2,505th star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in the category of television located at 6640 Hollywood Blvd. Lynch has lent her voice to multiple animated films, including ''[[Space Chimps]]'', ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]'', ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' and ''[[Wreck-It Ralph]]''. Since 2013, she has hosted the [[NBC]] game show ''[[Hollywood Game Night]]'', for which she has won two [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program|Emmy Awards]]. She has also hosted ''Earth Live'' for [[National Geographic (American TV channel)|National Geographic]].\n\n== Early life ==\nLynch was born in [[Evergreen Park, Illinois]],<ref>{{cite episode|season=11|number=2036|series=The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson|date=November 18, 2014|quote=Evergreen Park? I was born in Evergreen Park! [[Little Company of Mary Hospital (Evergreen Park)|Little Company of Mary]]. The hospital.}}</ref> and raised in [[Dolton, Illinois]], the daughter of a banker father, Frank Lynch, and a homemaker-secretary mother, Eileen (n\u00e9e Carney).<ref name=\"guardian10\">{{cite news | last = Berrin | first = Danielle | title = Jane Lynch: 'I'm just a goof' |work=The Guardian  | date = January 9, 2010 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jan/09/jane-lynch-glee-interview | accessdate =January 8, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Goldman |first=Andrew |url=http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Celebrity-Spotlight/Jane-Lynch/See-Jane-Run |title=See Jane Run |publisher=Elle |date=January 24, 2011 |accessdate=December 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130154943/http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Celebrity-Spotlight/Jane-Lynch/See-Jane-Run |archivedate=January 30, 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/books/titles/140503583/happy-accidents#excerpt |title=Happy Accidents by Jane Lynch |publisher=NPR |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref> Her father was of [[Irish people|Irish]] descent, his parents having come from [[Swinford]], [[County Mayo]],<ref>{{citenews | first=from Swinford | last=Grandparents | url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2016/0928/819919-jane-lynch-glee/ |title=Gleeful Jane Lynch leaves Ireland with full heart | publisher=RTE News |date=September 29, 2016 |accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last=Mayo | first=Grandparents |url=https://www.irishcentral.com/news/irishvoice/jane-lynch-on-adults-behaving-like-kids-in-acod-video-226322221-237793771\n| title=Jane Lynch on adults behaving like kids in A.C.O.D. | publisher=Irish Central |date=October 3, 2013 |accessdate= October 3, 2013}}</ref> and her mother was of Irish and Swedish ancestry.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bowles |first=Hamish |url=http://www.vogue.com/magazine/article/queen-jane-lynch/ |title=Queen Jane Lynch |publisher=Vogue |date=July 14, 2011 |accessdate=December 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110133629/http://www.vogue.com/magazine/article/queen-jane-lynch/ |archivedate=January 10, 2012  }}</ref> She was raised in a Catholic family<ref>{{cite web|last=Tecum |first=Dykeus |url=https://goodcatholicdykes.wordpress.com/tag/jane-lynch/ |title=Jane Lynch |publisher=Good Catholic Dykes |date=November 7, 2011 |accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> and attended [[Thornridge High School]].<ref name=\"guardian10\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n===Early work===\nLynch spent 15 years in Chicago, acting in the [[Steppenwolf Theatre Company]] and, at the time of her audition, was one of only two women picked to join [[The Second City]] comedy troupe.<ref name=\"guardian10\" /><ref name=tcea>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2012</ref> She then continued to hone her comical and [[improvisation]]al skills at [[Annoyance Theater]], playing [[Carol Brady]] in the theater's ''The Real Live Brady Bunch''.  [[Andy Richter]] played [[Mike Brady (The Brady Bunch)|Mike Brady]] in the New York shows.  He and Lynch became very good friends.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hernameisjanelynch.com/2010/07/12/jane-lynchs-panel-at-outfest-now-with-video | title = Jane Lynch at Outfest | work = Her Name is Jane Lynch | date = June 12, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110504163006/http://www.hernameisjanelynch.com/2010/07/12/jane-lynchs-panel-at-outfest-now-with-video/ | archivedate = May 4, 2011 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Films===\nLynch got her start in films in 1988, playing a small role in the film ''[[Vice Versa (1988 film)|Vice Versa]]''. In 1993, she had a secondary role as a doctor alongside [[Harrison Ford]] in ''[[The Fugitive (1993 film)|The Fugitive]]''.<ref name=Fugitive>{{cite book|author=Lynch, Jane|title=Happy Accidents|year=2011|publisher=[[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette Books]]|page=<!-- Ebook edition; page numbers not listed. -->|isbn=9781401342753|quote=This was a huge deal\u2014my first big Hollywood movie. I played Dr. Kathy Wahlund, a researcher and forensic scientist who helps Richard Kimble prove his innocence.}}</ref> She also appeared, in 1993, as a reporter in [[Fatal Instinct]].\n\nDuring the 1990s, she made numerous [[television commercial]]s, including one for [[Frosted Flakes]] for an adult audience, directed by [[Christopher Guest]]. A few years later, Guest would remember Lynch, as he chose actors for his 2000 dog show [[mockumentary]], ''[[Best in Show (film)|Best in Show]].'' Lynch played Christy Cummings, a butch lesbian personal dog handler to trophy wife Sheri Ann Cabot ([[Jennifer Coolidge]]). From there, she became a staple actress in Guest's casts, appearing in the director's ''[[A Mighty Wind]]'' (2003) as porn actress-turned-[[folk music|folk singer]] Laurie Bohner and in ''[[For Your Consideration (film)|For Your Consideration]]'' (2006) as an entertainment reporter.\n\nAudiences and critics took notice of Lynch for her turn in [[Judd Apatow]]'s ''[[The 40-Year-Old Virgin]].'' She told ''[[Fresh Air]]'s'' [[Terry Gross]] that the role was originally intended for a man but also that, at the urging of [[Steve Carell]]'s wife [[Nancy Walls]], was offered to Lynch instead.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=120086244 |title = The many roles of 'Glee' meanie Jane Lynch | work = npr.org | publisher = NPR | date = November 4, 2009 | accessdate =November 29, 2010 }}</ref> From there, she took supporting roles in a series of films including ''[[Role Models]],'' ''[[Talladega Nights: The Ballad of Ricky Bobby]],'' ''[[Alvin & the Chipmunks]],'' ''[[Walk Hard: The Dewey Cox Story]],'' ''[[Space Chimps]],'' ''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]],'' ''[[The Hammer (2007 film)|The Hammer]],'' ''[[Another Cinderella Story]],'' ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]],'' ''[[Wreck-It Ralph]],'' and ''[[Spring Breakdown]].''<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto Sun | url = http://www.torontosun.com/entertainment/movies/2009/08/18/10493296-sun.html | title = 40 is the new 20 for Jane Lynch  | first = Kevin | last = Williamson | date = August 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Adventures of Power,'' a critically acclaimed comedy about air-drumming released in 2008, Lynch reunited with [[Michael McKean]], her former co-star from ''[[For Your Consideration (film)|For Your Consideration]],'' in the role of Aunt Joanie and starring alongside [[Ari Gold (filmmaker)|Ari Gold]], [[Adrian Grenier]], [[Chiu Chi Ling]], and [[Shoshannah Stern]]. In a role similar to that of her contributions as [[Sue Sylvester]] on the [[comedy-drama|Fox musical comedy-drama series]] ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]],'' Lynch's role as the encouraging Aunt Joanie to Power, a young musician who plays the air drums because he never had access to musical instruments, promotes the initiative to support music education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bjupGPt0USQ |title=Power Saves the Music & The VH1 Save the Music Foundation in Jersey City |publisher=Youtube|date= |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Julie and Julia]],'' she portrayed Dorothy McWilliams, [[Julia Child]]'s sister. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' dedicated an article on its website to the possibility of her performance receiving an [[Academy Award]] nomination.<ref>{{cite web| last = Slezak | first = Michael | url =https://ew.com/article/2009/08/14/jane-lynch-julie-julia-oscar/ | title = Jane Lynch: How 'bout an Oscar nod for her work in 'Julie & Julia'? |work=Entertainment Weekly | date = August 14, 2009 | accessdate =February 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">\n{{cite web\n| last = Perry\n| first = Byron\n| title = Jane Lynch\n| date = March 5, 2008\n|work=Variety \n| url = https://variety.com/2008/scene/markets-festivals/jane-lynch-2-1117981898/\n| accessdate =February 24, 2020\n}}\n</ref> However, she was not nominated.\n\n===Television shows===\nLynch has appeared in many television shows, including ''[[The X Files]],'' ''[[L.A. Law]],'' ''[[Judging Amy]],'' ''[[The West Wing (television)|The West Wing]],'' ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]],'' ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', ''[[Friends]]'', ''[[NewsRadio]]'', ''[[Married With Children]]'', ''[[3rd Rock From The Sun]]'', ''[[Dawson's Creek]]'', ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'', ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'', ''[[Lovespring International]]'', ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'', ''[[Veronica Mars]]'', ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]'', ''[[Boston Legal]]'', ''[[The L Word|L Word]]'', ''[[Criminal Minds]]'', ''[[Help Me Help You (TV series)|Help Me Help You]]'', ''[[Gilmore Girls]]'', ''[[The New Adventures of Old Christine|New Adventures of Old Christine]]'', ''[[Psych]]'', ''[[Monk (TV series)|Monk]]'', ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]'', ''[[The King of Queens]]'' and ''[[Frasier (TV series)|Frasier]]''. She also starred with [[John Hannah (actor)|John Hannah]] and [[William Fichtner]] in 2002's ''MDs'' and has appeared in the crime drama ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' as [[Spencer Reid]]'s [[schizophrenic]] mother.\n\nIn 2008 she narrated ''Out & Proud in Chicago'', a documentary which tells about [[LGBT]] life in Chicago from the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] to 2008 through the stories of 20 everyday Chicagoans, from age 30 to age 80.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glhalloffame.org/index.pl?item=426&todo=view_item|title=Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame|access-date=December 27, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227201056/http://www.glhalloffame.org/index.pl?item=426&todo=view_item|archive-date=December 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jane Lynch at the 69th Annual Peabody Awards.jpg|thumb|right|Jane Lynch at the 69th Annual Peabody Awards for [[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]]]\nBeginning in 2009, Lynch appeared as a regular cast member of the Fox series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]].'' The role echoed previous guest appearances in ''[[The X-Files]]'' and ''[[Veronica Mars]],'' being her third time cast as a harsh high school teacher. She won glowing reviews for her role as the aggressive cheerleading coach, [[Sue Sylvester]]. Mary McNamara of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote, \"Lynch alone makes ''Glee'' worth watching.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Mary|last=McNamara|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-glee19-2009may19,0,3088358.story|title = 'Glee' on Fox| date = May 19, 2009|accessdate =October 11, 2010}}</ref> Before her work with ''Glee,'' she was a series regular on the [[Starz (TV channel)|Starz]] comedy ''[[Party Down]].'' Though the series was renewed for a second season, Lynch would not be returning, due to her work on ''Glee.''<ref name=\"partydown\">{{cite web|last = Godwin|first = Jennifer|title=Who Could Replace Jane Lynch on Party Down?|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b133021_who_could_replace_jane_lynch_on_party.html|date = July 7, 2009|publisher=[[E! Online]]|accessdate =July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nEven in ''Glee'''s early days, Lynch continued to pursue other projects. Lynch hosted ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on October 9, 2010; the news of her hosting was accidentally broken to her by her ''Glee'' boss, [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]], by text message.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.usmagazine.com/moviestvmusic/news/jane-lynch-found-out-shes-hosting-snl-by-text-2010118 | title = Jane Lynch Found Out She's Hosting SNL by Text| publisher = [[Us Weekly]] |work=[[Us (magazine)|Us]] | date = August 11, 2010 | accessdate =October 11, 2010}}</ref> Lynch had also guest-starred on the [[Nickelodeon]] comedy ''[[iCarly]]'' as Pam Puckett, Sam Puckett's mother, in the episode \"iSam's Mom.\"\n\nBeginning on July 11, 2013, Lynch hosted the NBC game show ''[[Hollywood Game Night]].'' The show had two teams made up of members of the public (civilians) and celebrities competing in various party games, with a chance for the civilians to take home up to $25,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/hollywood-game-night/ |title=Hollywood Game Night |website=NBC|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLynch was the co-host of the NBC special ''[[New Year's Eve with Carson Daly]]'' on December 31, 2013, alongside [[Carson Daly]], host of ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]].''\n\nIn February 21, 2017, Lynch appeared on ''[[The Price Is Right (American game show)|The Price Is Right]]'' as a Celebrity Charity Week contestant.\n\nIn March 2013, Lynch was announced as executive producer of comedy [[web series]] ''[[Dropping the Soap]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/digital/news/jane-lynch-lisa-kudrow-launch-digital-series-dropping-the-soap-1200006070/|title=Jane Lynch, Lisa Kudrow Launch Digital Series 'Dropping the Soap' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=AJ |last=Marechal |date=March 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref> Lynch starred in the series and was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Actress in a Short Form Comedy or Drama Series|Outstanding Actress in a Short Form Comedy or Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2017/outstanding-actress-in-a-short-form-comedy-or-drama-series|title=Nominees/Winners &#124; Television Academy|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref> The series premiered on [[Dekkoo]] and was made available on digital platforms including [[Amazon Video]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.out.com/television/2017/3/07/jane-lynch-fights-relevancy-dropping-soap|title=Jane Lynch on Her Hilarious Queer Web Series Dropping the Soap|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]] |first=Emily|last=Gaynor|date=March 7, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lynch portrayed [[Janet Reno]] for the [[Discovery Channel]] television series, ''[[Manhunt: Unabomber]]''.<ref name=\"RenoUnabomber\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/features/fl-fea-janet-reno-jane-lynch-discovery-channel-series-20170725-story.html |title=Jane Lynch plays the late Janet Reno in Discovery Channel miniseries|work=South Florida Sun-Sentinel|date=July 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2017, Lynch guest-starred in Episode 7 of ''[[Marvelous Mrs Maisel]]'' as popular but dislikeable comic Sophie Lennon.  Lynch returned in the role for two episodes at the end of the second season.<ref name=\"ET_Maisel\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.etonline.com/jane-lynch-teases-her-character-is-out-for-revenge-in-marvelous-mrs-maisel-season-2-exclusive|title= Jane Lynch Teases Her Character Is Out for 'Revenge' in 'Marvelous Mrs. Maisel' Season 2 (Exclusive) |work=ET Online |quote= \"Sophie Lennon, as you know, is a stand-up comedian, who in real life is a very smug, self-satisfied erudite woman,\" Lynch said.|date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Maisel\"/>\n\nIn 2019, Lynch joined the main cast of ''[[Final Space]]'' as A.V.A., the A.I. of the Crimson Light.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://animesuperhero.com/final-space-season-2-to-premiere-june-24-2019-on-adult-swim/|title= Final Space Season 2 to Premiere June 24, 2019, on Adult Swim |work=Anime Superhero |date=June 1, 2019 |accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\n===Other work===\nLynch wrote and starred in the award-winning play ''Oh Sister, My Sister.'' Originally produced in 1998, the play kicked off the ''Lesbians in Theater'' program at the [[Los Angeles Gay and Lesbian Center]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://movies.nytimes.com/person/43934/Jane-Lynch/biography | title = Jane Lynch |work=The New York Times | accessdate =June 4, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nShe starred in [[Comcast]]'s XFinity ads, mainly with two different laptops and two different colored [[Persian (cat)|Persian]] cats. She also stars in [[LG Corp.]]'s Text Ed campaign to educate drivers about the dangers of texting while driving.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hernameisjanelynch.com/2010/08/25/jane-lynch-is-a-text-ed-teacher | title = Jane Lynch is a Text Ed Teacher | work = Her Name is Jane Lynch | date = August 25, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nLynch's first experience hosting an awards show was in 2010 when she hosted the 2010 VH1 [[Do Something|DoSomething]] Awards.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/jane_lynch_VXO55skOqSLJYmdVAOyZFJ | title = Jane Lynch hosts DoSomething Awards, talks gay marriage, and Glee | publisher = [[The NY Post]] | access-date = July 11, 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111128195717/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/jane_lynch_VXO55skOqSLJYmdVAOyZFJ | archive-date = November 28, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It was announced that she will be hosting the 2011 VH1 DoSomething Awards, airing on VH1 on August 18.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/jane-lynch-to-host-2011-vh1-do-something-awards-120849449.html | title = Jane Lynch to Host 2011 VH1 Do Something Awards | publisher = [[PRNewswire]]}}</ref> Lynch hosted the [[63rd Primetime Emmy Awards]] on September 18, 2011, only the third woman in Emmy history to host the awards show solo.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/awards/2011/05/glee-on-fox-tv-jane-lynch-to-host-emmys-entertainment-news.html | title = Is Jane Lynch Going to Host the Emmys? |work=Los Angeles Times | date = May 24, 2011}}</ref> According to the edition of September 19 of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]],'' Lynch hosting the Emmys did not help ratings, as viewing was down 8% year over year and eight million fewer people watched the Emmys than watched Michael Vick's return to Atlanta on ''Sunday Night Football'' on NBC (21.5&nbsp;million for Eagles-Falcons, 13.5&nbsp;million for the Emmys).<ref>{{cite web|last=Guthrie |first=Marisa |last2=Powers |first2=Lindsay |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/emmy-ratings-expected-be-even-2010-2010-237168 |title=Emmy Ratings Down Among Viewers But Steady in Younger Demo |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=September 19, 2011 |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:GLEE JANE LYNCH LAURA EMBRY (wife).jpg|right|thumb|border|(l-r) Governor appointee [[Don Norte]], Dr. Lara Embry, Jane Lynch, and Norte's husband, gay activist [[Kevin Norte]], at Autum P-FLAG 2010's Charitable Event at The London Hotel, West Hollywood.]]\n\nAn autobiography written by Lynch, titled ''Happy Accidents,'' was published in the fall of 2011 by [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion Voice]]. Lynch was inspired to write the book after reflecting upon the successes of her past year and wishing she could have told her more anxious, younger self to not worry as much.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.hernameisjanelynch.com/2011/05/26/previews-of-happy-accidents |title=Previews of Happy Accidents | work = Her Name is Jane Lynch | date = May 26, 2011}}</ref> The memoir also includes detail about her years as an alcoholic and her success in battling this addiction.<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news|last=Newman|first=Judith|title=Jane Lynch Finds Herself|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/18/fashion/jane-lynch-finds-herself.html?pagewanted=2&_r=1|accessdate=September 18, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 16, 2011}}</ref> Lynch is openly lesbian and married Lara Embry in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|first=Hadley |last=Freeman |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/sep/19/jane-lynch-emmy-awards-glee |title=Jane Lynch: 'I came wired with extra angst' |work=The Guardian  |date=September 19, 2011 |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref> A self-proclaimed animal lover, Lynch has four [[rescue dog]]s.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Christine|last1=Copelan|accessdate=August 7, 2019|title='There's No Reason to Go to a Puppy Mill': Jane Lynch Talks Rescue Pets|url=https://parade.com/690455/ccopelan/theres-no-reason-to-go-to-a-puppy-mill-jane-lynch-talks-rescue-pets/|date=August 2, 2018|website=Parade}}</ref> She has recorded a [[Public service announcement|PSA]] for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] encouraging the adoption of shelter animals, and she sponsors an annual adoption event at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena.<ref>\"Jane Lynch Stands Up for Bitches,\" [http://www.ecorazzi.com/2011/02/01/jane-lynch-stands-up-for-bitches/ Ecorazzi] February 1, 2011.</ref><ref>Sue Manning,\"[http://www.salon.com/2013/05/16/glees_lynch_and_dog_go_to_bat_for_shelter_mutts/ Glee's Lynch and Dog Go to Bat for Shelter Mutts],\" Salon.com, May 16, 2013.</ref> She was the commencement speaker for [[Smith College]]'s class of 2012 where she received an honorary Doctorate in Fine Arts.\n\nIn March 2012, Lynch was featured with [[Martin Sheen]], [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], [[Chris Colfer]] and [[Brad Pitt]] in a performance of [[Dustin Lance Black]]'s play, ''[[8 (play)|'8']]'' \u2013 a staged re-enactment of the [[Perry v. Brown|federal trial]] that overturned California's [[Proposition 8|Prop 8 ban]] on [[same-sex marriage]] \u2013 as [[Maggie Gallagher]].<ref name=\"8 the play\">{{cite news |title='Glee' Stars 'Touched' By Pitt & Clooney's Support Of '8' |url=https://www.accessonline.com/articles/glee-stars-touched-by-brad-pitt-george-clooneys-support-of-8-114750|publisher=[[Access Hollywood]]|accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> The production was held at the [[Wilshire Ebell Theatre]] and broadcast on YouTube to raise money for the [[American Foundation for Equal Rights]].<ref name=\"8 play video\">{{cite web|title=\"8\": A Play about the Fight for Marriage Equality|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlUG8F9uVgM|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=YouTube to broadcast Proposition 8 play live|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/03/01/youtube-to-broadcast-proposition-8-play-live/|publisher=pinknews.co.uk|accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nLynch made her Broadway debut as Miss Hannigan in [[Annie (musical)|''Annie'']] for a limited engagement lasting from May 15 to July 14, 2013. She took the place of [[Katie Finneran]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 2014, Lynch joined the [[Ban Bossy]] campaign as a spokesperson advocating leadership roles for girls.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jolie Lee |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2014/03/10/ban-bossy-sheryl-sandberg-beyonce-gardner/6262309/|title=Beyonce, Jennifer Garner, Jane Lynch join 'Ban Bossy\" campaign|publisher=USA Today |date=March 10, 2014 |accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Lynch debuted ''See Jane Sing,'' a cabaret show in which she sings along with [[Kate Flannery]] from ''[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]'' and Tim Davis from ABC's ''Boy Band,'' accompanied by the Tony Guerrero Quintet. The show continues to tour around the country. In 2016, Lynch released ''A Swingin' Little Christmas'', a nostalgic Christmas album featuring the See Jane Sing ensemble and released on Lynch's own KitschTone Records label. The album received substantial airplay around the country and landed on the Billboard AC Chart's Top 10. In 2017, Lynch recorded a Christmas single with actor [[Dick Van Dyke]]. The song was composed and produced by [[Tony Guerrero]] and was released by KitschTone Records.\n\nIn 2020, Lynch directed her first 2 TV commercials for the production company, [http://www.storyco.tv STORY]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.shootonline.com/spw/jane-lynch-launches-career-commercial-director-story|title=Jane Lynch Launches Career As a Commercial Director via STORY}}</ref>, and joined its roster of commercial directors.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn 2005, Lynch was named one of [[Power Up]]'s \"10 Amazing Lesbian Women in Showbiz\". On May 31, 2010, in [[Sunderland, Massachusetts]], Lynch married [[clinical psychologist]] Lara Embry, whom she met a year earlier at a fundraiser in San Francisco.<ref name=NYTimesMarriage>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/06/fashion/weddings/06JLYNCH.html|title=Jane Lynch and Lara Embry|first=Paula | last = Schwartz|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 2, 2010|accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Schwartz2010-06-06\">{{cite news| last = Schwartz| first = Paula | title = Jane Lynch and Lara Embry| date = June 6, 2010| page = ST10 | newspaper = The New York Times | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/06/fashion/weddings/06JLYNCH.html| accessdate = October 11, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Everett2010-01-26\" /> In June 2013, Lynch announced that she and Embry were divorcing;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://people.com/celebrity/jane-lynch-divorce-glee-star-ending-marriage-to-lara-embry/| title=Jane Lynch and Lara Embry to Divorce | first= Monica | last= Rizzo | date = June 10, 2013 | accessdate= February 24, 2020|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref> the divorce was finalized in January 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/jane-lynch-divorce-finalized_n_4563177|title=Jane Lynch Finalizes Divorce From Wife Lara Embry  | first= April | last= Sperry |date = January 8, 2014| accessdate= January 8, 2014| work = [[HuffPost]]}}</ref>\n\nLynch is deaf in her right ear. On July 19, 2013, she speculated to [[Craig Ferguson]] on ''The Late Late Show'' that the deafness was most likely caused by having had a high fever as an infant.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Ferguson, Craig (host)|author2=Lynch, Jane (Guest)|title=Interview in season 9|work=The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson|date= July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLynch is \"kind of an [[atheist]].\"<ref>{{cite news|date=May 28, 2013|work=TMZ|url=https://www.tmz.com/2013/05/28/jane-lynch-athiest-glee-sneeze-god-bless-you/ |title=Jane Lynch: 'I'm kind of an Atheist'}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nHer portrayal of [[Sue Sylvester]] in ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' has won numerous awards, including the [[Primetime Emmy Award]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Jane Lynch Dedicates Emmy Award To Late Agent Gabrielle Krengel |url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/jane-lynch-emmy-award-dedication-late-agent-gabrielle-krengel-1201523743/ |accessdate=February 27, 2019 |work=Deadline |date=September 13, 2015 |language=en}}</ref> [[Golden Globe Award]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Jane Lynch |url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/person/jane-lynch |website=www.goldenglobes.com |accessdate=February 27, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]], [[TCA Award for Individual Achievement in Comedy]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernandez |first1=Sofia M. |title='Glee' tops TCA Awards |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/glee-tops-tca-awards-26140 |accessdate=February 27, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=July 31, 2010}}</ref> [[Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries, or Television Film]],<ref>Amy Rickman {{google books|5LsRBwAAQBAJ|Gleeful - A Totally Unofficial Guide to the Hit TV Series Glee|page=65}}</ref> and the [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award]] 2011 for Favorite TV Comedy Actress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Neel |first1=Julia |title=People's Choice Awards 2011 |url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/gallery/peoples-choice-awards-2011 |accessdate=February 27, 2019 |work=British Vogue}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2010\n| rowspan=2|[[Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series]]\n| ''[[Two and a Half Men]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]]\n| rowspan=10|''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Telev